me.tatarka.ipromise

Class Promise<T,E extends java.lang.Exception>

  • java.lang.Object
    • me.tatarka.ipromise.Promise<T,E>

  • public class Promise<T,E extends java.lang.Exception>
extends java.lang.Object
    A promise is a way to return a result the will be fulfilled sometime in the future. This fixes the inversion of control that callback-style functions creates and restores the composeability of return values.

    A example of an asynchronous method is as follows: 

    {@code
  async(arg, new Callback {
    See Also:
    Deferred

      • listen

        public Promise<T,E> listen(Promise.Listener<T,E> listener)
        Listens to a Promise, getting a result when the Promise completes. If the Promise has already completed, the listener is immediately called. This way you can't "miss" the result.
        Parameters:
        listener - the listener to call when the promise completes
        Returns:
        the promise for chaining

      • then

        public <B> Promise<B,E> then(Promise.Map<T,B> map)
        Constructs a new promise that returns when the original promise returns but, passes the result through the given Promise.Map function. If the result of the original Promise is not successful, the error or cancellation is passed through to the new Promise without invoking the Promise.Map function. This way you can do some work on an asynchronous result and pass it along without worrying about error or cancel states.
        Type Parameters:
        B - the success result type of the new Promise
        Parameters:
        map - the function to map the result of the original Promise to the new promise
        Returns:
        the new Promise

      • then

        public <B,ER extends java.lang.Exception,E2 extends ER> Promise<B,ER> then(Promise.Chain<T,B,ER,E2> chain)
        Constructs a new Promise that chains two promises in succession. If the first Promise is not successful, the resulting Promise immediately receives the error or cancellation and the second Promise is never called.
        Type Parameters:
        B - the type of the second Promise success result
        ER - the type of the second Promise error result
        E2 - the type of the new Promise error result.The reason this is a separate type is to allow chaining of promises with different error types. Since the original error may be passed through, this must be a superclass of both the first and second Promise error types.
        Parameters:
        chain - the Promise.Chain that constructs the second Promise
        Returns:
        the new Promise
